snippet.title: Mocking is hard. No it‚Äôs not! ‚Äì Mattia Assogna
snippet.description:
Find the latest React.js talks & workshops at https://portal.gitnation.org
¬†
¬† üóì Video recording from February 2019 meetup https://www.meetup.com/React-Amsterdam/events/257858463/

Testing is considered as standard practice in our industry. We use libraries to mock dependencies to test our code in isolation (e.g. services used in our React components). We take them for granted, assuming that they function correctly, probably by magic! Are mocking libraries ‚Äúmagic‚Äù?

Join Mattia to find out what libraries, such as Jest, are doing under the hood as you write your own mock testing library.

About Mattia
He loves shell scripting; he literally lives in the terminal (that‚Äôs probably why he uses VIM). Other than getting his hands dirty with React, RxJS and Mobx, he is also passionate about cyber security and Motorbikes.

ReasonML is based on the OCaml programming language and was created at Facebook, by the same creator as React! It shares a lot of features, but with the benefits of a statically typed functional programming language. ReasonML compiles to JavaScript and can therefore be used to create strongly typed React applications.

snippet.description:

# Breaking The Silence: Screen Readers and React Apps

When you rely on screen reader software to browse the internet, every important app update should be read out to you. However, this is often not the case in React applications, preventing many people from enjoying the awesome apps we make. Almero Steyn will put you in their shoes and then show you how to solve these issues easily and dependably. Many will thank you for it!

# Sending Email With React and AWS Lambda

Rendering templates is slow, and sending transactional email means rendering a LOT of templates. At Impraise, we built a system to handle rendering and sending email templates using AWS Lambda and server-side React. Now, our backend can simply call an API, and let Lambda handle the complicated part, and we'll gladly share details with you!

snippet.title: Florentijn Hogerwerf and Dirk-Jan Rutten: Lessons learned from implementing a GraphQL API
snippet.description:
Find the latest React.js talks & workshops at https://portal.gitnation.org
¬†
¬† üóì GraphQL is a query language for APIs that was released by Facebook back in 2015 and has since started to gain traction with both large and small companies using it for their APIs, most recently Github. 
As described on graphql.org:‚ÄúGraphQL provides a complete and understandable description of the data in your API, gives clients the power to ask for exactly what they need and nothing more, makes it easier to evolve APIs over time, and enables powerful developer tools.‚Äù 
We got introduced to GraphQL over a year ago and were impressed by its promise. Since then we have discovered patterns on how to best structure and implement a GraphQL API. In this talk we will share some of these patterns and provide examples on how to implement them.

Link to event page https://www.meetup.com/React-Amsterdam/events/237423993/

snippet.title: Maarten Verbaarschot: Routing for problem solvers
snippet.description:
Find the latest React.js talks & workshops at https://portal.gitnation.org
¬†
¬† üóì Maarten Verbaarschot, Frontend consultant @ Bluefront

Routing gets complicated quickly, conceptually and technically. My team learned several lessons when a seemingly tiny user story sent us right back to the drawing board, because our router couldn‚Äôt handle the scenario. Based on this experience, I will address several patterns that are available in modern routing frameworks. How to creatively leverage the router to solve problems? How to keep things simple? And seeing the router as the main player in wiring all components together: what can we do to make it a truly strong foundation?
